      "content": "A key way that a government might regulate the internet without becoming an engine of censorship lies in defining and implementing clear, narrowly tailored laws that are content-neutral as possible. This means regulations that affect all forms of expression equally, without targeting specific viewpoints. For instance, laws could focus on transparency and accountability without directly deciding which content is permissible.\n\n\nAdditionally, involvement of independent third parties or judicial oversight could help, where courts review and decide on the legality of content moderation measures so that these decisions are not made purely by governmental or corporate entities, maintaining a separation of powers. The concept of a digital bill of rights that includes guidance for transparency and due process in content regulation could further help insulate against censorship.\n\n\nLastly, a strong tradition of public discourse and feedback on regulations will necessitate government accountability without ceding authority on content. Still, it's crucial to recognize that this area is fraught with difficulties, and some level of debate regarding the extent and manner of regulation is inevitable in protecting both free speech and the public interest.",
